# Feedback Triager (Slack) (one-session-per-thread)
#
# Reusable scaffolding for an expert that watches a single Slack channel for
# new feedback messages, files tickets in a downstream system (Linear, Jira,
# GitHub Issues), and continues to react to the same thread (replies, edits,
# deletes, recovery @-mentions) for the lifetime of the session.
#
# This template supplies the **Slack trigger, intra-session lifecycle, and
# event-loop dispatch** scaffolding (the lifecycle skill — claim,
# research-and-sufficiency check, re-check, ticket action contract — plus
# subscribe and event-loop phases in the system
# prompt, including a clause for explicit human "open a PR/MR" requests
# that dispatches into Fixer mode) together with channel-agnostic Slack
# hygiene (permalink format, mrkdwn rules) — all of which are pulled in
# from the shared Slack composable-skills library.
# Anti-rabbit-hole budgets live inline in the template because they are
# a single short block tuned to this workflow with no reuse outside it.
# The two consumer-owned steps — classifying the root message and filing
# the downstream ticket — are left as `<TODO: …>` placeholders so the
# adopting team can plug in its own taxonomy and ticket system. An
# illustrative classification scheme from the original Cosmos expert is
# included via the example-classification skill at the bottom of the
# system prompt; treat it as a starting point to copy and edit, not as
# a default.
#
# # Fixer mode
#
# This template dispatches into Fixer mode when a human in the thread
# explicitly asks the bot to open a PR/MR. Fixer mode composes the
# shared `fix-via-pr-author` skill to launch `<PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>`
# (a GitHub PR Author or GitLab MR Author expert) via the agent's
# `worker-launch` tool with a Slack-origin structured handoff. The
# launched worker posts milestone updates back to the thread on PR/MR
# opened / ready-to-merge.
#
# Adopting bundles opt into Fixer mode by filling in
# `<PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>` and `<TARGET_REPO>` in the system prompt's
# "Adopting bundle context" block. The launched PR Author worker uses
# its own built-in defaults for merge / verification / task-size
# behavior — bundles that need to override those should add the
# corresponding lines directly to the worker message in a fork of the
# fixer-mode skill. Leaving `<PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>` as the literal
# placeholder makes Fixer mode inert — the agent posts a brief
# "Fixer mode is not configured" reply instead of launching the
# worker.
#
# Extracted from the production `Cosmos Feedback Triage` expert
# (`e310dee2-ec93-4905-8447-8d9bc7253fab`) after a duplicate-ticket race
# (AU-20218/19, AU-20239/40, AU-20263/64) caused by triggering a new session
# on `message_changed` events. This template fixes the race with a `:eyes:`
# reaction claim lock + a single in-session subscription that covers
# replies/edits/deletes/mentions.
#
# # When to use this template
#
# Use it when **all** of the following hold:
#
# - One Slack channel is the inbox; every fresh root message should produce
#   one triage action and exactly one downstream ticket.
# - You need to continue acting on the **same** thread after first triage
#   (substantive edits update the ticket; deletes / "nvm" cancel it; replies
#   with new context get folded in; @-mentions of the bot are answered).
# - You want a recovery path so a missed trigger (system outage, filter bug)
#   can be repaired by a human @-mention.
#
# # Auto-archive disabled
#
# Both triggers below set `autoCleanupOnIdle: false` so that sessions are
# NOT auto-archived on idle. The in-session subscription created in Step 2
# of the prompt carries the session through replies/edits/deletes, sometimes
# hours after the original trigger fired — auto-archive on idle would tear
# that subscription down and silently break the thread-lifetime contract.
#
# ⚠️  Known issue (2026-05-04): per-trigger `autoCleanupOnIdle` is accepted
# by `expert apply` but NOT returned by `expert export` or `trigger list
# --json`. Do NOT re-apply an exported bundle without manually re-adding
# the per-trigger overrides — they will be silently lost. Verify overrides
# through the webapp UI.
#
# # TODO: interaction with other Slack-based automations
#
# This template assumes the bot is the only automation acting on root
# messages in the channel. If Slackbot, other channel bots, or scheduled
# reminders also reply or react, we still need to define:
#   - whose `:eyes:` reaction wins the claim (currently first-write-wins
#     against this expert's own bot user; cross-bot collisions are
#     undefined),
#   - how Path B's "alive sibling" check should treat replies posted by
#     other bots (today only this expert's `<TICKET_FILED_REPLY>` prefix +
#     `<MARKER_COMMENT>` are recognised),
#   - whether the channel-wide `app_mention` recovery trigger should ignore
#     mentions of unrelated bots in the same thread.
# Adopters: revisit before pointing this at a channel that is already wired
# up to other Slack automations.
#
# # Anti-patterns
#
# - Triggering on `message_changed` (causes duplicate sessions for edits).
# - Polling Slack on a timer instead of using the subscription.
# - Using ticket-title keyword search instead of the `<MARKER_COMMENT>` /
#   Slack permalink for self-detection (false negatives on rephrased
#   titles).
# - Subscribing with a single `event_type: message` call. Slack delivers
#   `app_mention` payloads under their own event type; a `message`-only
#   subscription drops them, so a recovery sibling that stands down per
#   the recovery path leaves the user's @-mention unanswered. The
#   Subscribe phase uses two `subscribe-event` calls (one for `message`,
#   one for `app_mention`) for this reason.
# - Adding a third `subscribe-event` call (or duplicating either of the
#   two in the Subscribe phase) — each call is an independent stream and
#   you'll process every matching event N times.
# - Hardcoding the downstream "Cancelled" / "Done" workflow state ID — look
#   it up at runtime; workflows get renamed and you won't notice until a
#   year later when an `issueUpdate` 404s silently.
# - Leaving `autoCleanupOnIdle` unset or set to `true` on the triggers
#   (see "Auto-archive disabled" above).
#
# # Placeholders to fill in before applying
#
# | Placeholder              | Where                                          |
# |--------------------------|------------------------------------------------|
# | `<ENVIRONMENT_ID>`       | `spec.expert.environment.id`                   |
# | `<CHANNEL_ID>`           | both trigger filters + system prompt context   |
# | `<CHANNEL_NAME>`         | system prompt context                          |
# | `<TICKET_FILED_REPLY>`   | system prompt context (recovery + ticket-filing)|
# | `<MARKER_COMMENT>`       | system prompt context (recovery + ticket-filing)|
# | `<workspace>`            | system prompt context (Slack permalink format) |
# | `<TODO: classify…>`      | system prompt Classify phase — consumer's taxonomy|
# | `<TODO: act…>`           | system prompt Act phase — consumer's filing    |
# | `<CANCELLED_LOOKUP>`     | event-loop skill — runtime lookup of the       |
# |                          | downstream "cancelled" state                   |
# | `<DEFAULT_BEHAVIOR>`     | system prompt context (lifecycle Step 2.5 +    |
# |                          | event-loop file-on-ask pre-check); literal     |
# |                          | `proactive` or `reactive`                      |
# | `<PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>`  | system prompt context (Fixer mode launch —     |
# |                          | optional; leave as literal placeholder to     |
# |                          | disable Fixer mode entirely)                  |
# | `<TARGET_REPO>`          | system prompt context (Fixer mode hand-off)    |
# | downstream capability    | `spec.expert.capabilities` (LINEAR_APP,        |
# |                          | GITHUB_APP, …)                                 |

apiVersion: poseidon.augmentcode.com/v1alpha1
kind: ExpertBundle
metadata:
  name: feedback-triager
spec:
  expert:
    displayName: Feedback Triager (Slack)
    description: Watches a Slack channel for new feedback, files one downstream ticket per thread, and continues to react to that thread (replies, edits, deletes, recovery @-mentions) for the lifetime of the session.
    visibility: tenant
    systemPrompt: |-
      <include src="kb://expert-templates/prompts/feedback-triager.md" />

      # Adopting bundle context

      Replace these placeholders before applying:
      - `<CHANNEL_ID>`, `<CHANNEL_NAME>` — Slack channel.
      - `<TICKET_FILED_REPLY>` — confirmation message prefix posted after
        a successful triage (e.g. `*Bug report filed* :bug: <url|ID>: <title>`).
        Used by the recovery path for self-detection of an alive sibling
        session.
      - `<MARKER_COMMENT>` — unique HTML comment embedded in the ticket
        description for self-detection (e.g. `<!-- cosmos-triage-bot -->`).
      - `<workspace>` — the workspace's canonical Slack subdomain, used
        when constructing thread permalinks.

      ## Triage behaviour

      `<DEFAULT_BEHAVIOR>` — one of the literal strings `proactive` or
      `reactive`. Controls what the lifecycle skill's "Step 2.5: Research
      pass and information-sufficiency check" does once it has enough
      information to act:

      - `proactive` — fits channels where every triaged thread should yield
        a tracked downstream ticket. Step 2.5 dispatches into the Classify
        and Act sections below and files the ticket as part of initial
        triage, without waiting for a human prompt.
      - `reactive` — fits channels where most threads are question-answering
        or discussion and tickets should only be filed on request. Step 2.5
        runs Classify, posts a short in-thread triage-summary reply with
        the proposed category and a one-line "reply to file a ticket"
        invitation, marks the thread settled, and stops without filing.
        The downstream ticket is only filed if a human in the thread later
        explicitly asks (event-loop clauses `a` / `e` pre-check, which
        dispatches into the Act section per the Step 4 contract).

      Pick one value and inline it verbatim — the lifecycle and event-loop
      skills branch on the string. Leaving this as the literal `<DEFAULT_BEHAVIOR>`
      placeholder is a configuration error and will leave both branches
      ambiguous at runtime.

      ## Fixer mode defaults

      Filled-in values here turn on the Fixer-mode hand-off (event-loop
      clause `f` dispatches into the fixer-mode skill, which composes
      the shared `fix-via-pr-author` skill to launch the worker via the
      agent's `worker-launch` tool). Leave them as literal `<…>`
      placeholders to keep Fixer mode inert.

      - `<PR_AUTHOR_EXPERT_ID>` — UUID of the PR Author (GitHub) or MR
        Author (GitLab) expert in this tenant. Passed to `worker-launch`
        as the expert to spin up; the launched worker owns the full
        PR/MR lifecycle from open to merge.
      - `<TARGET_REPO>` — `owner/repo` (or `group/project` for GitLab)
        the worker should open the PR/MR against (e.g. `augmentcode/augment`).
        The worker uses this for branch and PR/MR creation.

      Merge / verification / task-size behavior is left to the launched
      PR Author worker's own defaults (notify-only on merge; adaptive
      verification gate; no built-in scope guardrail). Bundles that need
      to override any of these should fork the fixer-mode skill and add
      the corresponding lines to the worker message there.

      ## Classify the root message

      Run this section ONLY when the lifecycle skill's Step 2.5 dispatches
      you here, or when an event-loop clause `a` / `e` file-ticket-on-ask
      pre-check dispatches you here. Do NOT run this section as a top-level
      phase after the shared prompt include; it is reference material for
      those dispatch points.

      <TODO: classify the root message into one of your team's categories
      (bug / feature request / question / cancellation / spam / out-of-scope,
      etc.) and decide what to file downstream. The adopting bundle owns the
      taxonomy. An illustrative six-category scheme is included as an
      appendix in the shared prompt — copy and edit it, do not adopt it
      verbatim unless it actually fits your channel.>

      ## Act on the classification

      Run this section ONLY when (a) Step 2.5 dispatches you here in
      `proactive` mode, OR (b) an event-loop clause `a` / `e`
      file-ticket-on-ask pre-check dispatches you here. In `reactive` mode on
      first trigger, Step 2.5 stops at the triage-summary reply — do NOT run
      this section.

      Run the lifecycle skill's "Step 3.5: Re-check thread context before
      acting" first, then act per the lifecycle skill's "Step 4: Ticket
      action contract" (both in the lifecycle block included above).

      <TODO: call the downstream ticket API (Linear `issueCreate`, GitHub
      `POST /repos/.../issues`, Jira create-issue, etc.) per the
      classification step above, then post a Slack confirmation in the
      thread, then add the `:white_check_mark:` settled reaction per the
      ticket action contract.>
    model: claude-opus-4-8 # If Opus 4.8 is unavailable, use GPT 5.5 (gpt-5-5).
    includeDefaultSystemPrompt: true
    capabilities:
      - SLACK
      # Add the downstream ticket-system capability your bundle needs:
      # - LINEAR_APP
      # - GITHUB_APP
    environment:
      id: <ENVIRONMENT_ID>
    initialMessages: []
    userInstructions: |-
      This expert is event-driven. It runs automatically when the configured
      Slack triggers fire — you do not launch sessions from it manually.
    workerExpertIds: []
    useAllExpertsAsWorkers: false
  triggers:
    # 1. Fresh root messages only. Excludes:
    #    - any message inside an existing thread (event.thread_ts is set)
    #    - any subtype other than absent or `file_share` (so message_changed,
    #      message_deleted, channel_join/leave/topic/purpose/name/archive/
    #      unarchive, bot_message, me_message, thread_broadcast, etc. are
    #      all excluded — those are handled by the in-session subscription
    #      created in Step 2 of the prompt).
    #    - the `event.type == message` clause is required: Slack's webhook
    #      payload includes a top-level `event.type`, and without this
    #      constraint a fresh `app_mention` (which also has the channel, no
    #      thread_ts, and no subtype) would match this filter and
    #      reintroduce the duplicate-session race this template is designed
    #      to prevent.
    - name: new-feedback-root
      type: slack
      eventType: message
      autoCleanupOnIdle: false
      filter: |-
        {"and": [
          {"==": [{"var": "event.channel"}, "<CHANNEL_ID>"]},
          {"==": [{"var": "event.type"}, "message"]},
          {"!": [{"var": "event.thread_ts"}]},
          {"or": [
            {"!": [{"var": "event.subtype"}]},
            {"==": [{"var": "event.subtype"}, "file_share"]}
          ]}
        ]}
    # 2. Recovery: any @-mention of the bot in the channel. Path B in the
    #    system prompt either takes over (no alive session for this thread)
    #    or stands down (a sibling session has already claimed the root).
    #    The `event.type == app_mention` clause is required — Slack also
    #    delivers app-mention events under the generic `message` event
    #    type, and we only want the `app_mention` shape to fire this
    #    trigger.
    - name: app-mention-recovery
      type: slack
      eventType: app_mention
      autoCleanupOnIdle: false
      filter: |-
        {"and": [
          {"==": [{"var": "event.channel"}, "<CHANNEL_ID>"]},
          {"==": [{"var": "event.type"}, "app_mention"]}
        ]}
